07154nam a22007455i 9780822383598DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223835987 a10.1515/97808223835982doi  a(DE-B1597)553841  a(OCoLC)1167362556  a(OCoLC)1136177385  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0030002bisacsh00aLearning Places :bThe Afterlives of Area Studies /cMasao Miyoshi, Rey Chow, Harry Harootunian. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (424 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The ''Afterlife'' of Area Studies -- tIvory Tower in Escrow -- tAndo Shoeki-''The Forgotten Thinker'' in Japanese History -- tObjectivism and the Eradication of Critique in Japanese History -- tTheory, Area Studies, Cultural Studies: Issues of Pedagogy in Multiculturalism -- tSigns of Our Times: A Discussion of Homi Bhabha's The Location of Culture -- tPostcoloniality's Unconscious / Area Studies' Desire -- tAsian Exclusion Acts -- tAreas, Disciplines, and Ethnicity -- tCan American Studies Be Area Studies? -- tImagining ''Asia-Pacific'' Today: Forgetting Colonialism in the Magical Free Markets of the American Pacific -- tBoundary Displacement: The State, the Foundations, and Area Studies during and after the Cold War -- tThe Disappearance of Modern Japan: Japan and Social Science -- tBad Karma in Asia -- tFrom Politics to Culture: Modern Japanese Literary Studies in the Age of Cultural Studies -- tQuestions of Japanese Cinema: Disciplinary Boundaries and the Invention of the Scholarly Object -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnder globalization, the project of area studies and its relationship to the fields of cultural, ethnic, and gender studies has grown more complex and more in need of the rigorous reexamination that this volume and its distinguished contributors undertake. In the aftermath of World War II, area studies were created in large part to supply information on potential enemies of the United States. The essays in Learning Places argue, however, that the post-Cold War era has seen these programs largely degenerate into little more than public relations firms for the areas they research.A tremendous amount of money flows-particularly within the sphere of East Asian studies, the contributors claim-from foreign agencies and governments to U.S. universities to underwrite courses on their histories and societies. In the process, this volume argues, such funds have gone beyond support to the wholesale subsidization of students in graduate programs, threatening the very integrity of research agendas. Native authority has been elevated to a position of primacy; Asian-born academics are presumed to be definitive commentators in Asian studies, for example. Area studies, the contributors believe, has outlived the original reason for its construction. The essays in this volume examine particular topics such as the development of cultural studies and hyphenated studies (such as African-American, Asian-American, Mexican-American) in the context of the failure of area studies, the corporatization of the contemporary university, the prehistory of postcolonial discourse, and the problematic impact of unformulated political goals on international activism.Learning Places points to the necessity, the difficulty, and the possibility in higher education of breaking free from an entrenched Cold War narrative and making the study of a specific area part of the agenda of education generally. The book will appeal to all whose research has a local component, as well as to those interested in the future course of higher education generally.Contributors. Paul A. Bové, Rey Chow, Bruce Cummings, James A. Fujii, Harry Harootunian, Masao Miyoshi, Tetsuo Najita, Richard H. Okada, Benita Parry, Moss Roberts, Bernard S. Silberman, Stefan Tanaka, Rob Wilson, Sylvia Yanagisako, Mitsuhiro Yoshimoto  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aArea studieszUnited States. 0aArea studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aParry, Benita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilberman, Bernard S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCumings, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, H. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFujii, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiyoshi, Masao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoshimoto, Mitsuhiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiyoshi, Masao, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoberts, Moss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBove, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow, Rey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOkada, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTanaka, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYanagisako, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNajita, Tetsuo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eB